\begin_layout Standard
At the first step, a cell, 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

, is randomly selected from the set of all cells in the network, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 In a similar manner, a neighbor of cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

 is randomly selected in step 2.
 In step 3, the power difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n'$
\end_inset

 is calculated, based on (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:power_difference"

\end_inset

).
 After checking if the difference in the power levels of both cells is positive
 (step 4), a 0.1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

dB increase in the CPICH power level is saved in 
\begin_inset Formula $adj$
\end_inset

, in step 5.
 The power difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n'$
\end_inset

 is inspected again in step 6, but this time for a negative value.
 If this is so, a CPICH power level adjustement of -0.1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

dB is saved in 
\begin_inset Formula $adj$
\end_inset

, in step 7.
 Namely, the sign of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 indicates the direction of the CPICH power adjustment that should be applied
 over 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

 for the non-alignment to disappear, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

0.1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

dB power adjustments define the discrete nature of the search.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constraint defined in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:solution_constraint"

\end_inset

) is then checked over 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

 in step 8.
 If it is fulfilled, the move finishes in step 9 with the actual CPICH power
 change, by 
\begin_inset Formula $adj$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

dB, to cell 
\begin_inset Formula $c'$
\end_inset

.
 The acceptance of the move is left to simulated annealing.
 Otherwise, the whole process is repeated, beggining with a new random selection
 of a cell in step 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Test networks 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Test-networks"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All the test networks, 
\begin_inset Formula $Net_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Net_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $Net_{3}$
\end_inset

, are subsets of a real UMTS network deployed by Telekom Slovenije, d.d.,
 in Slovenia.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Net_{1}$
\end_inset

 represents a network deployed over a mostly rural area, where the network
 configuration emphasizes coverage over user capacity, since the resident
 population density is small.
 Network 
\begin_inset Formula $Net_{2}$
\end_inset

 represents a suburban area with a densly populated, but relatively small,
 downtown center, which contains a mixture of both urban and rural network
 configuration elements.
 The last network, 
\begin_inset Formula $Net_{3}$
\end_inset

, is deployed over a highly populated urban area, thus it presents a strict
 urban configuration profile.
 The three selected networks exhibit different operation and configuration
 schemes, depending on the dominant user's profile of each area.
 For this reason, the observed handover and soft-handover 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WCDMAforUMTS_RadioAccessForThirdGenerationMobileCommunications"

\end_inset

 behavior is fairly different among these scenarios, enabling the mobile
 operator to measure the impact of the optimization results given the particular
 conditions of each sub-network.
 Moreover, by challenging our optimization approach with problem instances
 of different characteristics and sizes, we are confident to gain better
 understanding about the optimization process itself.
 Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:network-properties"

\end_inset

 shows some key properties of the test networks presented.
\end_layout

