\begin_layout Subsection
Experimental environment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All experiments were done on a 4-core Intel i7 2.67 GHz desktop computer
 with 6 GB of RAM running a 64-bit Linux operating system.
 The implementation language used was Python, with certain parts of the
 objective function evaluation implemented in C, which improved the overall
 performance of the optimization process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:optimization-results"

\end_inset

 presents the best results obtained after 20 independent runs.
 We may observe that our optimization approach improved the objective significan
tly in all three problem instances.
 Results show that we have reduced the number of non-aligned neighbor relations,
 without changing the CPICH setting of any single cell for more than 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm$
\end_inset

2 dB, as it is defined by (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:solution_constraint"

\end_inset

).
 These results also indicate that the complexity of the problem quickly
 raises with the number of cells and neighbor relations in the network,
 since the achieved improvement is smaller for bigger networks.
 However, all tested problem instances are complex enough to make it very
 difficult and time consuming for an engineer to optimize them by hand.
\end_layout

